history of architecture lecture series john harwood history of architecture lecture series john harwood computer architectures between parlor and coal cellar although technical histories and sociological studies of the computer are hardly in short supply they all too often leave out a crucial fundamental fact computers are for seeing this lecture will explore how in the mid 20th century industrial designers and architects designed the visual and spatial character of the man machine system of the computer in explicitly architectural terms with numerous and lasting implications for the computer's spatial effects at scales ranging from the domestic to the geopolitical john harwood ph d architectural history columbia university 2006 is assistant professor of modern and contemporary architectural history in the department of art at oberlin college more information date and time monday march 8 2010 5 00 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s location cummings art building ar2 map audience faculty staff general public students category lectures readings sponsor department of art & art history contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free and open to the public download email event print use this permalink last modified february 25 2010
